title: For Sale:  Steiner Military 3-12x50 Rifle Scope First Focal Plane (FFP) Illuminated G2 Mil Dot Reticle
postcontent:
The Steiner 3-12x50 Military/Tactical Riflescope offers an exceptionally bright picture and a superbly flexible shooting range, making it suitable for long-range shooting or in-close tactical operations where a wider field of view is needed. No matter how you use it, you'll find the Steiner Military-Tactical 3-12x50 Rifle Scope to be rugged, flexible, and supremely functional. This Steiner Scope is fitted out with world-class Steiner optics, multi-coated for superior contrast and edge-to-edge sharpness. This waterproof military scope provides up to 5 mil of windage adjustment on each side, and up to 19 mil of elevation adjustment, with audible click adjustment knobs that give precise 0.1 mRAD/click adjustments. The shooter can adjust the parallax setting of the Steiner 3-12x50 Tactical Rifle Scope without taking their eyes from the scope. The Steiner 5312 Illuminated Rifle Scope features Steiner's G2 Mil-Dot reticle, a first focal plane reticle with 11 illumination brightness settings to keep you operating smoothly from the dimmest light to the brightest.

Though Steiner's site does not seem to specifically address manufacture and assembly the most reliable information I can find indicates that this scope features German made glass and is assembled in the USA.

Steiner's US reps have confirmed that this scope is covered by a lifetime transferable warranty.

For fans of TiborasaurusRex (Rex Reviews or Long Range 101) Rex just posted a review of this scope's slightly bigger brother, the 3-12x56 on YouTube:

Another helpful review can be found on the Sniper's Hide Forum from Jester308 (please note that this review is of the 4-16x50 rather than the 3-12x50 but that both scopes utilize the same 4x erector assembly to achieve their respective magnification ranges):

http://forum.snipershide.com/snipers-hide-rifle-scopes/178667-steiner-tactical-4-16x50-g2b-mildot.html

Other Useful links:

http://www.opticstalk.com/announcing-steiner-military-tactical-rifle-scopes_topic27102.html

title: For Sale:  Like new SCCY Industries CPX-2, 2 mags, lifetime warranty
postcontent:
Hello,

I have a SCCY Industries CPX-2 for sale. Purchased recently to check it out and consider as a new carry pistol (currently a Kahr CM9). The gun is rated very well in many publications. I put between 250 and 300 rounds through it.

The gun comes with box, papers, lock, 2 mags with either flush or extended base plates, and a lifetime warranty. It is no Glock, but it is a well made pistol. I found that while it has a long trigger pull, it is easy to shoot and accurate. I put it out to 10 yards and was shooting very well, even during rapid shooting. I fired 5 different FMJ rounds and 4 different HP and it did well with all except Armscor .124 gr. (feed issue on occasion).  It shot the Golden Sabre .124 + P with no problems.

The gun resembles a Kel-Tec P-11 but appears to be made much better. It uses stainless steel for the barrel and slide and has a good protective nitrate coating on slide. It is light, about 22 oz fully loaded w 11 rounds. Not as thin as my Kahr but it is lighter than my Glock 26 and appears to conceal easier (not as blocky).

So the gun is reliable, easy to conceal, and priced well. This would make a great CCW gun or a great backup. It just wasn't enough to replace my Kahr, so I am looking to sell. If interested, please feel free to call/text, Don REDACTED. Must have the firearm transferred at FFL. The cost to have that done is $25 and I will split the fee with you. Thanks, and have a great night. I have had a lot of time wasters lately so here is my FAQ section.

Q) I have XXXX for trade, are you interested?
A) NO, thank you, but not interested in any trades.

Q) Can we just do a bill of sale, I have a lifetime carry permit?
A) NO, through the FFL, sorry

Q) I will give you $200 for your SCCY.
A) Well first, that isn't a question, that is a statement. Second, NO you will not give me $200 because my price is $250. I am firm at that price, if it doesn't sell, oh well.

Q) I can get that same gun at XXXX for $XXXX.
A) Again, that isn't a question, that is a statement. If you can get it here or there for this or that, GREAT, go get it. I know what the prices are locally and online and mine is well within reason.

title: For Trade:  Mosin Chinese Type 53 - Restored!
location: Lake Villa, IL, Illinois, United States
postcontent:
Looking to trade a fully restored/refinished Chinese Type 53 Mosin Nagant. 

Entire rifle was stripped down, cleaned of cosmoline in a bath of mineral spirits for 1 week.

Bolt has been disassembled, polished, and cleaned.
All metal parts re-blued or touched up, butt plate duracoated, barrel bands reblued, etc. 

Chamber has been thoroughly cleaned and scrubbed (no sticky bolt on this one), and barrel thoroughly cleaned. 

Headspace checked with OKIE GO, NO GO, and Field guage. Good to GO! 

Strong riffling and groves.  Most T53’s do NOT come with a cleaning rod. I picked one up from an online vendor, but can’t confirm if it’s Chinese or Russian. The seller said it was Chinese, but after looking at some cleaning rod variants, can’t confirm either which way. The cleaning rod screws in flawlessly and fit’s perfectly though. 

If you're familiar with what's on the market, all the T53's stocks are rough! Not much out there in quality “Chue” wood (original chinese wood on T53’s) so started to restore the stock. The wood that the Chinese used is particularly soft and doesn’t take well to stain and is a PITA to work with. 

Ended up completely stripping the stock - it was rough, sanding from 300 grit to 1200/000 steel wool. The original stock was almost a dark chocolate brown and was beat to death, so to get even  stain, ended up bleaching the stocks to level out the colors. Chroline didn’t work so well, so bleached with multiple treatments of Oxalic acid. This went on for over 3 months in my spare time. 

Stained with a custom mixed dye to get closest match to what the color might have been originally. Photos do not accurately reflect the light, but it’s a shade lighter with a hint of orange/brown VS the Russian “RED” Nagants. 

Finished off with 22 coats of Tru-Oil over 6 months. Has a High Gloss sheen right now, but can easily be knocked down with 000 steel wool for a "matte finish". Tru-oil is easier to work with and touch up than Poly and I prefer it for gun stocks! 

The stock is gorgeous and is the original Chue wood!!!! 

Negatives: This T53 is NOT numbers matching and there was a small patch on the stock that you can see in the photos. Right side near the crossbolt. Not very noticeable, but it's there. 

I wont’ say the stock is perfect, but it’s damn nice! I doubt you’ll find a better Type 53 and one that is pure Chinese Chue wood that came with the T53’s. 

Lot’s of photos attached! 

**** IF INTERESTED IN A TRADE, CONTACT ME FROM ARMSLIST! PLEASE INCLUDE NAME AND NUMBER! No Name/no number, I WILL NOT RESPOND!!!
